seed_chunks:
Dockside power splits three ways. The Harbor Authority sells itself as safety and regulation, but its old families quietly launder “accidents” into paperwork to keep the Calder sea-debt contained and profitable. The Brinehand Union, public champions of longshoremen and night labor, runs protection and “lost cargo” recovery—while feeding chosen names to the water in exchange for calm tides and steady work. Across both moves the Tideglass Fellowship, a charitable maritime heritage society; beneath the varnish it’s a cult mapping bloodlines and timing ritual drownings to tighten the sea-god’s claim. The Authority leans on Union muscle, the Union resents Authority crackdowns, and Tideglass plays them against each other with favors, fog, and fear.

```json
{
  "factions": [
    {
      "name": "Harbor Authority",
      "public_front": "Port safety, licensing, inspections, and incident response.",
      "hidden_agenda": "Old families bury ritual drownings as “accidents,” steering investigations and payouts to keep the Calder sea-debt managed and monetized."
    },
    {
      "name": "Brinehand Union",
      "public_front": "Longshoremen’s union protecting workers, wages, and night-shift conditions.",
      "hidden_agenda": "Runs dockside protection and discreet recovery; offers select victims to the sea-god to secure calm waters and guaranteed work."
    },
    {
      "name": "Tideglass Fellowship",
      "public_front": "Maritime heritage charity funding buoy upkeep, sailor memorials, and community aid.",
      "hidden_agenda": "Cult conducting and scheduling ritual drownings, tracing bloodlines (including the Calders) to strengthen the sea-god’s claim and leverage."
    }
  ]
}
```

Fog has settled for three nights straight, and with it the water has started giving bodies back—each with Harbor Authority “accident” tags already stamped, as if the paperwork beat the tide. Commissioner Lysa Harrow orders a midnight “safety sweep” that’s really a purge of witnesses. The Brinehand Union answers with an unofficial strike and roving pickets, shaking down shops for “protection” while they hunt whoever’s disrupting their offerings. Meanwhile the Tideglass Fellowship announces a candlelit memorial on Pier Nine, quietly timing it to a rare tide window—Rafe’s name surfacing in their ledgers.

```json
{
  "events": [
    {
      "name": "The Returned With Paperwork",
      "description": "Bodies surface with Harbor Authority accident tags already filed, implying a coordinated cover-up. Commissioner Lysa Harrow launches a midnight 'safety sweep' to seize footage, silence witnesses, and steer investigations away from ritual signs.",
      "tensions": [
        "Witnesses and dockworkers risk disappearing during the sweep",
        "Rafe’s clients may be forced to hand over security logs or lose permits",
        "Evidence of ritual drowning is being laundered into official reports"
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Pier Nine Memorial Tide Window",
      "description": "Tideglass Fellowship stages a public candlelit memorial at Pier Nine while privately aligning it to a rare tidal convergence for a new drowning. The Brinehand Union’s unofficial strike and patrols escalate violence as they hunt the saboteur threatening their sea-deals.",
      "tensions": [
        "Public crowd becomes cover for an abduction or sacrifice",
        "Union enforcers and Authority patrols could clash on the piers",
        "Tideglass ledgers circulate a Calder bloodline marker—putting Rafe on a clock"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

